Using the new NAU Tagger

Author of this tutorial: Larissa Goulart
Operating system: Windows
Tested on 08/28/2020

Before we start

The goal of this tutorial is to teach you how to tag your corpus with the new NAU tagger. You will need to download:

     1. CLAWS

  • Download CLAWS and AntCLAWSGUI. Don’t forget to unzip the files and to save both programs in the same folder.
    You can download both together here

     2. New NAU Tagger

  • Download the files of the new NAU Tagger

     3. Python

  • Download Python

     4. Practice files

  • If you need you can download a folder with some txt files to practice here.

Overview

Here is a general overview of this tutorial:

      1.Preparing the files
      2.Running CLAWS7
      3.Running the new NAU Tagger

1.Preparing the files

If your files are not in .txt format, or encoded in utf-8, you won’t be able to run the new NAU tagger. Here is a way to convert, encode and standardize your files.
If your files are ready, skip to step 2.

1.1. Corpus Text Processor

We will use CROW’s Corpus Text Processor to prepare the files. I recommend that you create three folders in your computer that mirror the menus in the Corpus Text Processor: 01_converted, 02_encoded, and 03_standardized before running the tool. It should look like this.

And this is what you will see when you open the Corpus Text Processor

To convert the files, we will follow the order of the menus in the Corpus Text Processor. You can also watch the video demonstration on how to run it.

2.Running CLAWS7

2.1. Save all the files in the same folder

  • Unzip the CLAWS7 files
  • Save AntCLAWSGUI in the CLAWS7 folder

It should look like this on your computer:

2.2. Annotating your corpus with CLAWS7

  • Open the AntCLAWSGUI interface

  • Open the files or directory you want to tag

File> Open File(s)/Open Dir..

  • Select the second Input Files box

  • Keep the Horizontal setting checked
  • Press Start

  • Copy the tagged files to a new folder

  • It is important to have the NAU Tagger and your files in the same directory.

Here is how it looks like on my computer:

3.Running the new NAU Tagger

3.1. Create a folder where you will save the tagged files

Remember to create this file in the same directory.

Here is how it looks like on my computer:

3.2. Navigating to the bibertagger-tagger folder

  • Open Power Shell ISE

  • Use dr or ls to list the folders in your directory

  • Use cd to navigate to the directory where you saved the bibertagger-tagger folder

If you run into an error, check that you are doing cd + space + the name of the folder. You can also use tab to autocomplete the name of the directory.

Once you find the folder you are looking for, press Enter

This is how it should look like:

I saved the bibertagger-tagger folder in my documents. So, in my computer, this is the code I need to type:

cd Documents\new_tagger\bibertagger-tagger

3.3. Running the new NAU Tagger in a folder

To annotate a whole directory, this is the code you will use:

python claws2biber.py path to the input directory path to the output directory

This is how the code will look like on my computer:

python .\claws2biber.py '..\Practice files' '..\Practice files_tagged'

Where ..\ means that I am going back one folder.

This is how it looks like on my computer:

The files will be saved with a tec extension, to change that you can add the flag --ext txt to the code.

Then, the code will look like this:

python .\claws2biber.py '..\Practice files' '..\Practice files_tagged' --ext txt

THE END
